        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Glenrhydding House | Patterdale | Penrith</placeName>
                    <date>June 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> 1881</date>
                    <salute>My dear Paget</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged for your extremely kind invitation for Augt 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>, which I consider a great honour &amp; have much pleasure in accepting.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> You will see by the above address why there has been some delay in answering your note.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I remain | Yours very sincerely | Charles Darwin</p>
<p>We remain here for 4 or 5 weeks</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 Penrith] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘<hi rend="italic">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>’ </note>
            </div>
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13188.xml">letter from James Paget, 1 June 1881</ref> and n. 1.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The Darwins visited Patterdale in the Lake District from 3 June to 4 July 1881 (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242)).</note>           
        </div>  
      
